  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These efforts are primarily coordinated through various international organizations and agreements. Here are some key components:\n\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: Established in 1989, the FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF Recommendations are considered the global standard for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF).\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**: Several UN conventions address money laundering:\n   - **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Also known as the Vienna Convention, it requires signatory states to criminalize the laundering of money derived from drug trafficking.\n   - **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions for combating money laundering related to organized crime.\n   - **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: This convention includes measures for preventing and combating money laundering.\n\n3. **European Union Directives**: The EU has issued several directives to combat money laundering:\n   - **First EU Money Laundering Directive (1991)**: Aimed at preventing the use of the financial system for money laundering.\n   - **Subsequent Directives**: The EU has continued to update and strengthen its AML framework, with the latest being the **Sixth EU Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, which came into effect in December 2020.\n\n4. **Basle Committee on Banking Supervision**: Although not a legislative body, the Basle Committee has issued guidelines that influence global banking practices, including those related to AML.\n\n5. **Other Regional Organizations**: Various regional organizations have also established AML frameworks, such as the **Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG)**, the **Caribbean Financial Action Task Force (CFATF)**, and the **Intergovernmental Action Group against Money Laundering in West Africa (GIABA)**.\n\nThese international laws and frameworks require member states to implement measures such as customer due diligence, reporting of suspicious transactions, and the establishment of financial intelligence units (FIUs). However, the effectiveness of these laws often depends on the willingness and capacity of individual countries to enforce them.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
